.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.65,"Integration":0.1,"System":0,"Agentic":0.25,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The number of tokens consumed for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"A Unit test that mocks token counts at the function level cannot detect the real failure: that the module's tokenization logic differs from the external API's tokenizer (different algorithm, special tokens, overhead), causing actual API calls to exceed the budget despite passing Unit tests. To catch this failure, we must verify token counting against a realistic tokenizer that matches or approximates the external API's actual tokenization. Integration level with a real tokenizer library (e.g., OpenAI's tiktoken for GPT) is the minimum; testing against the live API (Agentic) would be stronger but is not the minimum required level.","test_description":"Create an integration test using a real tokenizer library that matches the external API's tokenization scheme (e.g., OpenAI's tiktoken for GPT-based APIs). Create test documents at various sizes near the configured budget boundary. Call the classification module and assert that (a) documents within budget are accepted and (b) documents exceeding budget are rejected or truncated such that the actual request stays within limits. Verify token counts against actual tokenizer output.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Integration-level testing with a real tokenizer catches the mismatch failures that Unit-level mocking would hide. This is necessary to ensure the module's estimate matches the API's actual behavior.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.65,"System":0,"Agentic":0.25,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"The real failures (returning an erro